Description: You receive a business gift of $20,000. You can only apply this $20,000 to a business debt and you must do it on this turn only. You may not make a purchase with it.
You pay the college tuition for one of your family members. That family member becomes a lawyer. All your legal fees are free.
You do a Trade Show for one of your businesses and get some new clients. Choose one of your businesses and roll a PayDay roll right now.

A friend gives you a suggestion on a stock to buy. Place your investment amount on the table and roll. The result, multiplied by $1,000, is the amount of each share of stock. You can buy this stock now if you would like.
You reserve a private Yacht for a week long vacation. Roll both die, multiply the result by $3,000. Pay the Bank your vacation cost and lose your next turn basking in your private sun.
Your parents give you $20,000 towards starting a new business or investing in your current business. Choose which and play according to the game rules.

You inherit a business from your Father. Decide the type of business it is, what the name of the business is, whether it is a home-based or brick & mortar business and include it into your game play. Pay a $20,000 transfer fee. If you do not have $20,000 in cash, you cannot have the business.
You donate money to the survivors of a wild fire. The news runs a segment on you and your Brand increases. On the next Pay Day, receive double your profits on all businesses.

You buy a television station and convince every player in the game to market on your station one time. You receive 50% of all the marketing dollars currently on the board. Round to the nearest $1,000 if needed.
You reserve a private Island for a month long vacation. Roll both die, multiply the result by $2,000. Pay the Bank your vacation cost and lose your next turn basking in your private sun.
Roll both dice twice. If you roll a total of 19 or more, receive all of the money currently in every player’s marketing account that is on the table.
Your parents give you $20,000 towards starting a new business or investing in your current business. Choose which and play according to the game rules.

You inherit a business from your Father. Decide the type of business it is, what the name of the business is, whether it is a home-based or brick & mortar business and include it into your game play. Pay a $20,000 transfer fee. If you do not have $20,000 in cash, you cannot have the business.

Choose a player and buy half of one of their businesses. Roll two die, multiply by $3,000 and pay the player that amount for 50% interest in their business. You can choose not to, but you must make that choice before you roll.

You buy a television station and convince every player in the game to market on your station one time. You receive 50% of all the marketing dollars currently on the board. Round to the nearest $1,000 if needed.
Your television ads fail to yield good results; you lose all of the money in your marketing account. Give it to the Bank.

You put an ad on Facebook for your business. Roll the dice: 1 - If you roll a 6 or lower, you lose all of the money in your marketing account 2 - If you roll a 7 or higher, your ad nets you 800% of the total money currently in your marketing account

Your ad contains false claims and result in a government investigation. You lose your entire Marketing Account, plus pay lawyer fees of $3,000 per business to the bank. If you have a lawyer, you do not have to pay the extra $3,000 in fees, per business.
Word of Mouth advertising is taking off for your business. Your Marketing Account triples, but you must leave it in the account.
You hire a Marketing Firm to market your business but it yields no results. You lose your entire marketing account to the Bank. Plus pay $5,000 for their services.

You begin a new marketing campaign. Roll 1 die. If it is an even number, your campaign is successful and you receive all of the money in your marketing account back plus 500%. If it is an odd number you lose all of the money in your marketing account.
If you can create and sing a jingle for your business in the next 60 seconds, you will receive all your marketing money back, plus 800% profit per business from the Bank.
Your billboard ad fails to yield any profit. You lose all of the money currently in your marketing Account. Give it to the Bank.
Radio Ad yields no ROI (Return on Investment). You lose all of the money currently in your marketing Account; Give it to the Bank.
You sponsor a charitable project, which results in positive media press. Receive all of your Marketing Budget back, plus 700% profit from the bank.
You hire a Marketing Firm to market your business but it yields no results. You lose your entire marketing account to the Bank. Plus pay $5,000 for their services.

You do an infomercial. Tell us what it looks like in 30 seconds and receive all of your Marketing Budget back plus 600% profit from the Bank. If you cannot, lose your entire marketing budget to the Bank.

You market your brand so well a larger company wants to buy one of your businesses. If you agree, choose a business and roll 2 die, multiply the result by the amount in your marketing budget. If it is you only business that you are selling, you must restart the game from the beginning.
You publicly back a candidate for political office and they turn out to be a jerk. Your Brand takes a huge hit. You lose all of the money in your marketing account to the Bank.

You begin a new marketing campaign. Roll 1 die. If it is an even number, your campaign is successful and you receive all of the money in your marketing account back plus 500%. If it is an odd number you lose all of the money in your marketing account to the Bank.
Your location catches on fire and there is severe damage. Lose your next turn while rebuilding.
Your employee embezzles money from your business. Roll 2 dice, multiply by $5,000 and pay it to the Bank. If you have a lawyer you lose 50% of the total bill currently owed.
Damage to the electrical grid results in a 4‐  day total power outage in your City. You lose all your business profits on next Pay Day.
Yearly business insurance premium is due. Pay $2,000 to the Bank for each Home-Based business, $5,000 for each Brick & Mortar business.

Your employee claims you sexually harassed them, but you did not. You can either;  1 - Settle out of court and pay them $50,000. 2 - Take your chances in court. Roll 2 dice and pay $10,000 times the number rolled.
A car drives into the side of your building. If Business #1 is Home Based, pay a $5,000 Insurance Deductible; if Brick & Mortar $10,000 deductible.
Hurricane Damage: Extensive damage to all of your home based businesses. Insurance will rebuild with no deductible, but you lose your next Pay Day for all of your home-based businesses.
Your business (es) fails a Tax Audit. You are fined 50% of your current liquid cash. If you have a lawyer, your fine is reduced to 20% of your current liquid cash.

A customer is injured at one of your business locations. You can either;  1 - Settle out of court and pay them $25,000. 2 - Take your chances in court. Roll 2 dice and pay $5,000 times the number rolled.
Your computer has been hacked! You catch it in time, but you must buy more security for your business records. Pay $20,000 to the Bank.

Mold is discovered in all the buildings of your Brick & Mortar businesses. Roll 1 die and multiply by $3,000. Pay that total amount to the Bank to clean the buildings of your Brick & Mortar businesses.
A customer accuses you of sexual harassment and your brand takes a hit. Roll 2 die; multiply the result by $2,000 and pay the Bank. If you have a lawyer, the loss is cut in half.
You make a business deal with a friend who goes to jail for fraud. You are investigated as well. If you have a lawyer, pay $10,000 to the Bank. If you do not have a lawyer, pay $25,000 in fees.
You have not been taking care of your health and you become too ill to work. You lose half of your income on your next Payday.

You make a comment on Social Media that is going viral in a bad way. All of your businesses suffer because of it. You lose half your income on the next two Paydays. If you have a lawyer, lose half your income on only one Payday
You run for a local Government office and win. You create a Bill whose effects doubles your income on the next Pay Day.
You write your Autobiography and it becomes a Best Seller. Roll 1 die, multiply result by $5,000 and receive your income from the Bank.
You go to an Estate Auction and buy a painting that turns out to be valuable. You can sell it now, roll both dice, multiply result by $10,000 and receive profits from the Bank.
Your business is audited by the IRS and you have not been keeping very good records of the income and expenses for your business. They fine you $30,000. If you have a lawyer, your fine is $15,000.

You can become a vendor at a local Jazz Festival for a vending fee of $20,000. If you accept, pay the Bank $20,000 and roll two die; multiply the result by $5,000 and receive your vending income from the Bank.
You sue a company for Defamation and win. Choose a player and receive all of their profits on their next Pay Day.
A relative passes away and you are the sole beneficiary of their life insurance policy. It is enough to pay off your loan for your Brick & Mortar Business.
Roll both die and multiply the result by $7,000. You can sell any one of your current Businesses to the Bank for that price right now. If it is your only business, you must start from the beginning.

You are sued for Trademark Infringement and you lose. If you have a lawyer roll 1 die, multiply by $1,000 and pay to the Bank. If you do not have a Lawyer, roll two die and multiply by $2,000 and pay to the Bank

You may take out a Bank loan of $50,000, but you must invest it in a business partnership with another player. You both become 50% owners. You share income and expenses 50/50 for the rest of the game. They chose what the business is and the name of the business.
You have been honored by the Mayor for your community involvement. Your Brand increases; on your next Payday, receive double your business profits on all of your businesses.

You can become a vendor at a local Jazz Festival for a vending fee of $20,000. If you accept, pay the Bank $20,000 and roll two die; multiply the result by $5,000 and receive your vending income from the Bank.

A large corporation wants to buy all of your businesses except for one. You must decide before you roll. Choose which one business to keep and roll 2 die for each business you are selling; multiply each result by $10,000 and receive your income from the Bank.

The City is adding a bus line that runs in front of your business. If you own a Brick & Mortar business, on your next Payday, you receive double your income for one Brick & Mortar business. You must announce which business receives this bonus before you roll.

Choose a player and you both roll 2 die. The person with the lower roll must pay the other player $10,000. If it is a tie, roll until there is a winner. If the losing player does not have $10,000 cash, you will become 50% owner in one of their businesses, your choice of which business.
